<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / Russians meet 'stiff resistance'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Russian army units yesterday continued to pound Chechen positions to the
north of the capital of Grozny but were meeting what the Russian Interior
Ministry admitted was 'stiff resistance' and are still holding back from an
assault. Despite mounting protests at home and abroad, the government
continues to show a will to squeeze the city, if not yet take it. A meeting
of officials chaired by Prime Minister Victor Chernomyrdin promised further
'decisive action,' saying that the army was preparing to cut minor roads to
the south of the city. A statement released after the meeting spoke of
Chechen forces retreating to the hills, while those which remained used
civilians as 'human shields'. The government press service maintained that
the 'city is in panic'. But these reports are not wholly confirmed by
journalists still in Grozny. Western military analysts in Moscow believe
seizure of the city is being delayed until it is as empty as possible and
until surrounding Chechen forces have been weakened. While talks were still
being called for yesterday, these are now thought all but impossible.
Meanwhile, the foreign ministry said Russia was closing its borders with
Georgia and Azerbaijan to prevent the movement of rebel fighters in
Chechnya.
A very Bosnian plight, Page 14
</TEXT>
