<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / Pact defuses Gibraltar drugs trade row: Spain to ease
'intrusive frontier checks' following complaints by London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain and Spain yesterday defused a diplomatic row over Gibraltar by
agreeing to develop more formal arrangements for tackling drugs trafficking
and other illicit trade between the UK colony and the Spanish mainland.
A joint statement issued after talks between Mr Douglas Hurd, the UK foreign
secretary, and Mr Javier Solana, his Spanish counterpart, in London, said
that both sides had recognised there was 'a problem of illegal trafficking
in the Gibraltar area'. Both ministers agreed to establish a 'mechanism',
which should include Gibraltarian officials, to 'improve consultation and
co-operation' between all three sides.
Mr Hurd said the authority would consists of 'two flags (Spain and the UK)
and three voices (Spanish, British, and Gibraltarian)'; in other words, that
the move would not impinge on either country's sovereignty claim over the
colony.
However, Spanish officials feel the proposal is a concession by the UK in
that it potentially allows Madrid a greater say in Gibraltarian affairs.
Spanish concerns that the UK was not doing enough to prevent Gibraltar
becoming a big drugs smuggling and money laundering centre led Madrid
earlier this month to step up border controls.
The move fuelled resentment within Gibraltar and drew a diplomatic protest
from the UK over what London claimed were 'intrusive' checks by Spanish
police.
Yesterday Spain agreed to lift secondary checks at the Gibraltar border to
pave the way for greater diplomatic co-operation with the UK within the
wider context of the EU.
Mr Solana, in an interview, hailed the agreement on the illicit trade as a
breakthrough in talks which underlined points of common interest on EU
matters but which otherwise made little headway on long-standing differences
over sovereignty in Gibraltar.
'The Gibraltarian economy has to be put on a more healthy footing. You
cannot have an economy which is not sound,' he said.
Mr Hurd said separately: 'I made clear to Mr Solana that intrusive frontier
checks were not welcome. . . and stressed the need to build up confidence.'
According to officials, both sides agreed, at least for the foreseeable
future, to disagree on the issue of sovereignty rather than risk a
confrontation with the Gibraltarian government.
Mr Joe Bossano, Gibraltar's chief minister, has lashed out recently at both
London and Madrid whom he has accused of approving a 'dirty tricks' campaign
to destabilise his government.
But yesterday Mr Hurd appeared to have appeased Mr Bossano by reiterating
the UK commitment to a clause in Gibraltar's 1969 constitution. This
guarantees that the UK will not cede the colony to Spain against the wishes
of the majority of the population.
Last night the Gibraltarian government issued a conciliatory statement of
its 'desire to work in close co-operation' with the UK and 'in harmony with
its neighbour'.
</TEXT>
