<HEADLINE>
FT  21 DEC 94 / Kuwait is offered Pounds 1.5bn for property company
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Pounds 1.5bn offer to buy the St Martins Property group, the leading
property business owned by the Kuwaiti government, has been made by Barings,
the London merchant bank, on behalf of an investment consortium.
St Martins owns some of London's most valuable property, including the strip
on the south bank of the Thames known as London Bridge City. Only half of
that site has been developed.
It also owns other prime developments, such as the City headquarters of the
Kuwait Investment Organisation, the Kuwaiti government's international
investment arm, and offices, retail developments and industrial units in the
UK and on the Continent.
The bid is the most dramatic indication to date that investor confidence in
the property sector may be returning.
Although property prices have recovered from their lows of two years ago,
the share prices of leading property companies have performed much worse
than the market average this year.
Barings has yet to receive an official response from the Kuwaiti government
but a senior official last night appeared hostile to the proposed sale.
Dr Yousef Al-Awadi, general manager of the KIO, said the government was not
soliciting offers: 'As far as we are concerned, it is not for sale,' he
added.
The offer was made late last month at a meeting in Kuwait between Barings,
accompanied by the London arm of French bank Credit Lyonnais, and Mr Ali
Rashid Al-Badr, who is in charge of the Kuwaiti government's investments. It
was repeated in a fax sent just over a week ago.
The value of St Martins' assets is uncertain because most are held directly
by the Kuwaiti government through a nominee company, St Martins Property
Investments, and their value is not disclosed in accounts filed at Companies
House.
Under this arrangement Kuwait benefits from a convention that assets owned
directly by a sovereign or government are immune from taxes.
A former Kuwaiti government official said yesterday that the properties were
valued at Pounds 1.9bn at their peak in the late 1980s, before the property
recession.
Last year the St Martins group paid an estimated dividend of Pounds 60m to
Kuwait. This year's payment is expected to be lower.
A financier associated with St Martins said the group's development was
being held back by a shortage of capital.
The Kuwaiti government bought St Martins in 1974, in a bidding contest with
property group Commercial Union.
Since the 1991 Gulf war, Kuwait has been selling some of its more liquid
investments, although it has retained the majority of assets, such as St
Martins, which are not quoted on the stock market.
</TEXT>
