<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Profits taken after Dow's
recent gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA BRANSTEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices retreated from Friday's gains yesterday as traders took
profits after last week's advance, writes Lisa Bransten in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended 16.49 off at 3,790.70. The Standard &amp;
Poor's 500 lost 0.89 at 457.91, the American Stock Exchange composite eased
0.50 to 425.73 and the Nasdaq composite shed 1.16 to 727.91. New York Stock
Exchange trading volume came to 272m shares.
Analysts attributed much of last week's strength to Friday's
'triple-witching hour' when options and futures on stock indices expired
together in the last 60 minutes of trading. With that out of the way and no
important economic news out yesterday, there was little to push up the
market.
Investors were also acting cautiously in advance of today's meeting of the
Federal Reserve's open market committee. Most analysts are betting that the
Fed will not lift rates at the meeting, but opinion is not unanimous.
Interest rate rises usually push the market down as investors worry that
reduced consumption and borrowing will erode corporate earnings.
In recent weeks the market has moved up and down skittishly as investors
first worried about another rate rise and then bought when those fears
subsided briefly. A round of relatively mild economic news put out last week
led many to speculate that the Fed would not raise rates again before
January.
Caesars World rocketed Dollars 20 3/4 to Dollars 66 after ITT said it would
acquire the casino company for Dollars 67.50 per share, or Dollars 1.7bn.
ITT dipped Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 81 1/2 .
US Shoe rose Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 19 after an investor group at the
company said it would back the sale of its footwear business to Nine West,
Dollars  3/8 firmer at Dollars 26 5/8 .
Ben &amp; Jerry's fell Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 10 after the ice cream company
announced that it expected a fourth-quarter loss of Dollars 700,000 to
Dollars 900,000 and a decline in revenues from the same period last year.
Revenues should be about Dollars 30m, the company said.
Canada
Toronto stocks were no worse than mixed as Wall Street declined. Hearty
gains in banking shares and golds provided the bulk of the fuel for a rise
of 18.72 points to a closing 4,136.75 for the TSE 300 index. Declines and
rises were almost evenly matched at 385 to 384 after volume of 55.7m shares.
Ten of the 14 sub-indices advanced, led by gold, financial, communication
and industrial-product stocks. Conglomerates, consumer products, oils and
merchandising posted the biggest declines.
The golds group added 0.91 per cent, even though the New York spot bullion
price eased 35 cents to USDollars 379.75 an ounce.
Mexico
Equities finished sharply lower after reports came through of fresh trouble
in the southern state of Chiapas. The IPC index dropped 95.93 or 4.12 per
cent to 2,231.66  - at the end of 1993 it stood at 2,602.63. Volume was a
modest 31.2m shares worth 390.4m new pesos.
The Zapatista rebels said they had turned down an offer from the government
of a multi-party commission to negotiate peace. Traders said key Mexican
rates are likely to see increases at the central bank's weekly auction
tomorrow because of nerves stemming from Chiapas.
</TEXT>
