<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / International Company News: Xerox agrees to sell reinsurance
subsidiary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Xerox, the US document processing company, has agreed to sell a reinsurance
subsidiary for Dollars 400m, the largest disposal to date in the planned
break-up of its financial services businesses.
The company, Constitution Re, has been bought by Exor, a Luxembourg-listed
investment holding company controlled by the Italian Agnelli family.
Xerox early last year announced plans to sell off its financial services
businesses, with the exception of the financing operations which support
sales of its office equipment products.
The move echoes steps taken by several other big US non-financial companies
to leave the financial services business, which they had once seen as a
fast-growth industry in which to invest surplus profits.
Since announcing its plans, Xerox has sold Van Kampen Merritt, a fund
management firm, for Dollars 360m and Furman Selz, an investment bank, for
Dollars 90m. Constitution Re is the eighth-largest US-based reinsurer, with
net premiums last year of Dollars 454m, according to Xerox.
It writes reinsurance for a number of small US property and casualty
insurers, and takes on little catastrophe risk, according to Talegen,
Xerox's property and casualty insurance subsidiary.
The disposal, for cash, will leave Xerox a life insurance company and six
specialist property/casualty insurance businesses, which had premiums last
year of Dollars 2.4bn.
</TEXT>
