<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / International Company News: US group buys Kraft Foodservice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Clayton, Dubilier &amp; Rice, the US leveraged buy-out specialist, has agreed to
buy Kraft Foodservice, the second-biggest food service company in the US,
from Philip Morris, the US food and tobacco group.
The price was not disclosed, but is believed to be about Dollars 700m.
Kraft Foodservice is part of Kraft General Foods, Philip Morris's food
company. It distributes industrial-size packages of foods to restaurants,
hospitals and other non-retail outlets. Annual revenues are about Dollars
4bn.
The company distributes more than 160,000 products from different suppliers,
including Kraft General Foods. As part of the deal with Philip Morris, Kraft
Foodservice will remain the exclusive distributor of Kraft-branded food
service products to most customers for five years.
Clayton, Dubilier &amp; Rice, a private investment firm, specialises in
acquiring divisions of big corporations and working with their managements
to improve returns. In the past year it has bought Wesco Distribution from
Westinghouse Electric, Remington Arms from Du Pont, and Allison Engine from
General Motors.
The firm seeks to increase the profitability of acquisitions by asking
managers to a take a stake in the business so that they have an incentive to
improve its performance. Kraft Foodservice's management is believed to be
participating in the Kraft transaction.
Under Philip Morris, Kraft Foodservice had been closely associated with Mr
Michael Miles, the former chairman and chief executive who resigned earlier
this year. He turned it into the biggest food service company in the US
after Sysco.
Mr Geoffrey Bible, the new chief executive of Philip Morris, is under
pressure to improve the company's performance, as its share price has been
battered by fears about possible consequences of anti-tobacco litigation.
</TEXT>
