<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / International Company News: Burlington increases offer for
Santa Fe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The stakes in the contested bid for the Santa Fe Pacific railway company
have been raised with an increased offer from Burlington Northern valuing
Santa Fe at Dollars 3.8bn in cash and shares.
The bid is a sharp increase on the offer from rival railway company Union
Pacific of about Dollars 3.2bn in cash and shares.
The merger aims to create the biggest railway group in the US.
Burlington and Santa Fe said they would both make cash tenders for Santa Fe
stock, amounting to about one-third of the equity, at Dollars 20 a share.
Thereafter Burlington would offer a stock swap for the remainder of Santa
Fe's equity.
While the cash element of the transaction would take place next month, the
stock swap would not take place until government approval of the merger.
The offer from Union Pacific, although lower, has the advantage of having
been provisionally cleared by the authorities. Its offer is allowed to
proceed immediately, with Santa Fe's shares being placed in an independent
trust pending official clearance.
Santa Fe also said its agreed deal with Burlington involved a poison pill
payment to Burlington of up to Dollars 60m if the agreement fell through.
Santa Fe said it would repay Dollars 400m of its outstanding debt.
</TEXT>
