<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / Trafalgar in Pounds 1.2bn offer for Northern: Customers
promised Pounds 20 rebate - Rec spurns 'financially challenged' bidder
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH and DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first contested takeover bid in the UK utility sector was under way last
night as Northern Electric, the regional power company for north-east
England, rejected a Pounds 1.2bn offer from Trafalgar House.
Northern's board said it could see no advantage to its shareholders in
becoming part of a 'financially challenged conglomerate, effectively
controlled by an offshore minority shareholder'.
Hongkong Land, a subsidiary of Bermuda-based Jardine Matheson has a 25 per
cent stake in Trafalgar.
If Trafalgar succeeds with its bid, signalled last Wednesday, it intends to
offer a Pounds 20 rebate to each of Northern's 1.3m to 1.4m customers.
Analysts believe that could set a precedent for future takeovers in the
sector.
Mr Brian Wilson, Labour party industry spokesman, predicted an orgy of bids
and mergers involving privatised utilities, offering 'the prospect of
guaranteed risk-free profits at the public expense'. He called for the bid
to be referred to the Mergers and Monopolies Commission.
The bid is also being considered by Prof Stephen Littlechild, industry
regulator. Mr Nigel Rich, Trafalgar chief executive, said Prof Littlechild
had told him on Sunday that he would be consulting publicly, although the
regulator's office was unable to confirm this last night.
Mr Simon Keswick, Trafalgar chairman, said he did not believe the bid would
be referred to the MMC. 'In our judgment, it is unlikely,' he said. Mr Rich
said Trafalgar wanted friendly discussions with Northern's management. 'We
have attempted to talk to them but they said they want to see our offer
first.'
Northern's shareholders are being offered Pounds 44.35 in cash and 65 new
Trafalgar convertible preference shares for every 10 shares they hold. With
the convertibles down 3 1/2 p to 94 1/2 p yesterday this valued each
Northern share at Pounds 10.58. There is also a full cash alternative of
Pounds 10.48 a share compared with Northern's close of Pounds 10.18, up 33p.
Northern shareholders can opt to obtain part of the consideration in the
form of 'grids', interest-bearing bonds which give them rights to shares in
the National Grid, 6.5 per cent of which is owned by Northern, if it is
floated next summer.
For these purposes, Trafalgar estimates that each Northern share contains
Pounds 2 for the Grid element. This implies a market capitalisation for the
Grid of about Pounds 3.5bn against City estimates of more than Pounds 4bn.
Grids will be tradeable and a grey market is expected to develop after the
offer document goes out.
Hongkong Land has agreed to buy the first Pounds 310m of preference shares
to meet elections for the cash alternative, Following implementation of the
offer, it could hold up to 31 per cent of the ordinary shares of Trafalgar
assuming full conversion. However, it said it had 'no present intention' of
holding more than 30 per cent of ordinary shares.
Trafalgar is advised by Swiss Bank Corporation and Northern by SG Warburg.
Observer, Page 15; Lex, Page 16;
Background, Page 18; East Midlands results, Page 20
</TEXT>
