<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / OECD predicts 2 years of steady growth for UK: Low inflation
and better job prospects expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain can expect at least two more years of steady economic growth, the
Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development said yesterday.
In its latest half-yearly outlook, the Paris-based body, which represents 25
leading industrial nations, adds that the present economic upturn should be
healthier than previous recoveries. Inflation will remain relatively low
even though unemployment will fall significantly.
But the organisation urges the British government to raise interest rates
again to curb any inflation. It predicts that bank base rates will rise to 7
per cent next year, and to 7.5 per cent at the start of 1996. Although this
marks a significant increase, the OECD says UK interest rates should remain
well below the peaks seen in previous cycles.
'The current recovery differs from previous upswings in several respects . .
. controlling inflation may be possible with lower interest rate rises than
in the past as monetary and fiscal policies have been tightened much earlier
in the cycle,' it says.
One factor that may help keep inflation down, the OECD suggests, is the
relatively high level of spare capacity estimated to exist in the UK
economy.
In spite of mounting concern in the City that recent strong growth could be
overheating the economy, the OECD says the UK has more spare capacity than
any of the leading seven industrial nations. It calculates that the UK
output gap, which represents the difference between potential and actual
growth, is 4 per cent.
In addition, the report says the structural reforms that occurred in the UK
during the 1980s may help keep interest rates low.
The OECD gives a cautious welcome to the deregulation of the UK labour
market. The changes which have taken place in recent years mean falling
unemployment may not push up inflation as fast as in the past, it says,
predicting unemployment will fall below 8 per cent in the next two years.
Although the report was written before the recent Budget and interest rate
rise, it says the tax increases introduced earlier this year should slow the
pace of recovery slightly next year.
Gross domestic product is predicted to grow by 3.4 per cent next year,
slowing to 3 per cent the following year. This is slightly more optimistic
than the Treasury's forecast of 3.25 per cent growth next year. Inflation is
forecast to remain relatively low next year, but is expected to rise to 2.6
per cent in 1996.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, said the report was 'very encouraging'.
In a separate report, however, market research group Gallup pointed to a
worsening 'feel-bad' factor in the UK. It said yesterday that its December
survey of consumer confidence showed a sharp increase in the number of
households expecting their financial position to worsen next year.
Consumer confidence falls, Page 6
Research spending grows, Page 6
