FT  20 DEC 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Christmas is already influencing scheduling trends: old films, a quiz and
ancient comedy are in evidence tonight. Among the oldies I would happily
plump for the repeated Only Fools and Horses (8.30 BBC1) above the others.
Not quite Christmassy is Sex in a Cold Climate (9.00 C4). No, not a
permissive update of Nancy Mitford but a documentary on Ann Summers, the sex
shops I fondly imagined run by a liberated Hampstead-dweller in a Laura
Ashley smock. The chain is actually owned by a group whose interests include
porn mags, which adds a sinister edge to the shots of housewives shrieking
at jolly sex-aids selling parties. Whatever happened to Tupperware? Don't
answer - they have probably found an unmentionable use for that as well.
Is tonight the last pre-Christmas sex (sorry, adult programme) binge? The
Ballad of Nicky Mouse (12 midnight C4) is not quite unmentionable, merely
unspeakable. Homosexuality in prison inspired the Jean Genet film Un Chant
d'amour but this pretentious drivel is not, emphatically not, it.
