<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / Companies face bridge snub
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Scottish Office is likely to reduce the role of the private sector in
drawing up and promoting the project for a second road bridge across the
Firth of Forth.
It is expected instead to design the project itself and submit it to a
public inquiry before a decision is taken on whether to proceed.
The change of strategy, expected to be announced early in the new year, is
likely to be seen as a climbdown by the Scottish Office in the face of
strong opposition to a new bridge, mainly from people in Edinburgh and other
parts of Lothian.
It may also be viewed as a setback for the government's private finance
initiative, under which the government wants big construction projects to be
designed, financed and built by the private sector as far as possible.
Studies of the area around the Firth of Forth for the Scottish Office of
transport have concluded that a second road bridge would be needed in the
first decade of the next century.
The government was widely expected to announce that it had decided a package
of road and public transport improvements  - including a new bridge  - and
to invite tenders from private sector consortia to design, build, finance
and operate the improvements. The entire scheme would almost certainly have
faced a public inquiry when finalised, although this was never made clear by
the government.
Instead it appears likely that the transport scheme, including a new bridge,
will be developed by the Scottish Office and submitted to a public inquiry
before a decision is taken on whether to go ahead with it.
If the public inquiry concluded that a second road bridge was necessary, the
project would be put out to tender to be built and financed by the private
sector, with the risk borne by the private sector reduced.
Scottish Office ministers are understood to be drawing lessons from the
Birmingham northern relief road project, where the private-sector consortium
of Trafalgar House and Iritecna (of Italy) is facing a second public inquiry
which further increases the risk that the project will not go ahead, as well
as involving extra costs.
Four consortia of leading UK and European construction companies, as well as
banks, have registered an interest in tendering to build the bridge.
</TEXT>
