<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / CU fined Pounds 105,000 over tied company
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Financial services regulators have imposed a Pounds 105,000 fine on the life
insurance subsidiary of Commercial Union, one of the UK's biggest composite
insurers, over the quality of one of its representative companies, Alison
Smith writes.
Compensation totalling Pounds 185,000 has already been paid to 58 investors
by CU Life Assurance, and the subsidiary has undertaken that other investors
will be compensated. It will also pay the regulator's costs of Pounds
25,000.
The problems relate to the activities of an appointed representative  - a
company 'tied' to a life insurer and selling its products only  - where CU
ended the relationship more than two years ago.
The penalty was imposed by Lautro, the self-regulating organisation for the
life insurance industry, now superseded by the Personal Investment
Authority, which acts as regulator for retail financial services.
Lautro said CU Life Assurance had failed to ensure that one of the
representatives was of good character and of requisite aptitude and
competence and had also failed to satisfy itself about the good character
and competence of the senior management of the tied agent.
CU said yesterday that it had improved its procedures.
</TEXT>
