<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / NUT leadership calls for end to test boycott
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The leadership of the National Union of Teachers yesterday recommended that
its members end their boycott of national curriculum tests after the
government agreed to hold a wide-ranging consultation into the tests'
educational value.
The move, which may herald the end of two years' industrial action over the
issue, follows a meeting last week between Mr Doug McAvoy, the union's
general secretary, and Mrs Gillian Shephard, education secretary.
All three teachers' unions boycotted the tests when they were introduced to
secondary schools in England and Wales last year. Two abandoned their
boycott last year after concessions by Mr John Patten, then education
secretary, but the NUT remained strongly opposed to them.
Mr McAvoy said the union's position had been strengthened by last week's
announcement that only 20 per cent of secondary schools reported the results
of English tests for 14-year-olds this year. He said this showed the boycott
was still strong.
He described the agreement as a 'tremendous achievement' for the union's
campaign. The deal would lead to a consultative exercise similar to the
consultations carried out by Sir Ron Dearing during his two-year review of
the national curriculum, he said.
Mrs Shephard, who had already announced in September a Pounds 30m package of
measures including external markers to placate teachers, suggested the
consultation would be less ambitious. 'As in previous years,' she said, the
School Curriculum and Assessment Authority, chaired by Sir Ron, would
evaluate the tests.
She said: 'I have taken a series of steps to respond to teachers' concerns
about workload and to enhance teachers' professionalism. I am glad that the
NUT executive has responded in a professional and considered way.'
Mr McAvoy said Mrs Shephard's 'willingness to understand the professional
and educational concerns of teachers' had made the announcement possible.
The union will ballot its members on the proposal, and will lift the boycott
if a majority are in favour.
However, Mr McAvoy made clear the union would continue to support members
who claim that the tests create an unreasonable workload. This is in line
with the policy of the other teachers' unions.
The NUT leadership continues to claim that the tests are 'educationally
unsound', a view endorsed by 90 per cent of members who responded to a
survey in October. Members telephoned the union yesterday afternoon to
protest at the apparent deal.
</TEXT>
