<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / Family tax cost will rise to 35.6%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The amount of tax the government takes from the average family is set to
rise again next year, further denting the Conservatives credentials as the
party of low taxation, David Owen writes.
New figures released last night by the Treasury show that a married man on
average earnings, with two children, will pay 35.6 per cent of his earnings
in direct and indirect taxes in 1995-96  - up from 34.7 per cent in the
current financial year.
This outstrips the 32.2 per cent that a similar family would have paid in
1978-79, when the Labour party was last in power.
When the government acknowledged in January that its 1993-94 tax take would
amount to 32.8 per cent of an average family's earnings, the disclosure was
immediatedly pounced on by the opposition parties.
Sir George Young, financial secretary to the Treasury, replying to a written
question by Mr Andrew Smith, Labour MP for Oxford East, said that tax
increases taking effect over the next year would cost households on average
about Pounds 2.30 a week.
He added that real personal disposable income was still expected to rise by
1 1/2 per cent next year. 'This should mean that households will on average
be about Pounds 5 a week better off after tax and inflation,' he said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
