<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / Howard rejects calls to resign over jail break-out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, yesterday rejected Labour demands for
his resignation after he released a report into a break-out by five
terrorists and an armed robber from Whitemoor prison in Cambridgeshire.
The report by Sir John Woodcock, former chief inspector of constabulary,
blamed the escape on management confusion that allowed 'pampered' inmates to
take advantage of lax security. He said: 'So many things were wrong, so many
procedures and policies totally ignored, and with such regularity, that the
escape could have taken place on any day of any week with the same chance of
success.'
Mr Howard told the Commons that the break-out, and the subsequent discovery
of a pound of Semtex explosive at Whitemoor, happened because the prison
service failed to follow written instructions.
He said a separate report drawn up before the break-out by Judge Stephen
Tumin, the inspector of prisons, concurred in the general view in the prison
service that Whitemoor was 'virtually impregnable'.
Mr Howard announced a further inquiry by Sir David Yardley, the former local
government ombudsman, into whether there was sufficient evidence to bring
disciplinary charges against members of the prison service.
A separate inquiry by Sir John Learmont, the former quartermaster general
for the army, will review security in all prisons, including the possible
introduction of glass screens to prevent contact between inmates and
visitors.
Mr Howard said security had been tightened at Whitemoor and prisoners'
perks, such as use of telephones, excessive personal property and sending
warders to do their shopping, had been stopped.
He added that Mr Derek Lewis, director-general of the prison service, had
agreed 'there will be no question of a bonus' this year. Mr Lewis was paid a
bonus of Pounds 35,000 for the year to March.
The Whitemoor escapers, armed with two pistols smuggled into the prison,
escaped by cutting fencing and climbing another fence with rope made in the
prison workshop.
</TEXT>
