<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / Israeli markets tax to go ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIAN OZANNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Israeli prime minister Yitzhak Rabin yesterday said a controversial capital
gains tax would go ahead on January 1 as planned. The statement put an end
to a cabinet row over the proposed measure and settled more than a week of
uncertainty. It would mean Israeli investors would have to pay tax of 10 or
20 per cent on stock market profits, depending on whether they wanted to
deduct their losses. The option with deductions would be assessed at 20 per
cent of net profits and would require investors to file year-end tax
reports. The option without deductions would be assessed at 10 per cent and
would be deducted at source.
Mr Rabin made the announcement after meeting Mr Abraham Shochat, the finance
minister, who has spent the last week fending off fierce criticism of the
tax from other ministers. Opponents maintained the proposals had hit support
for Mr Rabin's Labour party.
</TEXT>
