<DATE>941220
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / Fresh US attempt to reform banking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jim Leach, the incoming chairman of the House banking committee,
yesterday outlined an ambitious programme of banking legislation, parts of
which will be launched early in the new year.
The series of bills will include legislation to reform the Glass-Steagall
Act, which separates many aspects of commercial and investment banking in
the US, and an initiative to reduce the number of agencies responsible for
banking regulation.
Mr Leach, currently Republican minority leader of the committee, also
outlined plans for legislation to cover the derivatives markets, and to give
the US administration powers to retaliate against countries which shut out
US financial services companies.
Plans for reform of Glass-Steagall have foundered before on wrangles between
the different interest groups involved. Many big US commercial banks, along
with foreign banks operating in the US, have argued strenuously for greater
freedom to trade and underwrite securities, and to enter the insurance
business.
Mr Leach said this was the 'first and most important' issue facing the
banking industry, and that he would introduce a bill on the first day of the
new Congress to end the barrier between commercial and investment banking.
The incoming chairman also hinted at a more moderate plan for consolidation
among bank regulators than that attempted earlier this year, which would
have led the Federal Reserve to giving up its bank regulation powers.
Mr Leach, while praising the Fed, said the Office of Thrift Supervision,
which overseas the savings and loans industry, looked 'increasingly
superfluous'.
A bill on derivatives would not be introduced until 1996, he added.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
