FT  20 DEC 94 / Italian ministers in threat to quit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Italian government was further undermined yesterday by the prospect of
ministers from the populist Northern League resigning in advance of
tomorrow's no-confidence vote in parliament.
At least three of the five League ministers said they preferred to resign
their portfolios before voting against the right-wing coalition of which
they formed part.
Mr Giancarlo Pagliarini, finance minister, went further and became the first
minister to criticise openly Mr Silvio Berlusconi, the Italian premier, by
claiming 'he lacked the ability to run the government'.
But Mr Berlusconi still won support  - albeit lukewarm  - from Mr Roberto
Maroni, interior minister and the most influential League figure in the
cabinet.
Backers of Mr Umberto Bossi, the League leader, were gathering signatures
from among the deputies within the movement yesterday to check those willing
to vote against the government.
Mr Bossi has tested the loyalty of a sizeable number of deputies by turning
towards the former communist Party of the Democratic Left (PDS) as a
potential ally. Others are concerned that, since their election was due to
strong backing from Mr Berlusconi's Forza Italia movement, they cannot
easily break this link without betraying the electorate.
However, the League is aware that the government has little chance of
survival. The party's stance will be crucial for the eight-month-old
government in the three no-confidence motions due to be debated on
consecutive days.
The financial markets registered their concern over the increasing
instability by forcing the lira to fall close to another psychological
barrier  - L1,050 to the D-Mark.
</TEXT>
