<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / Carter claims ceasefire offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PALE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jimmy Carter, the US peace mediator, yesterday claimed that the Bosnian
Serbs had agreed an immediate ceasefire and that they were willing to
discuss the international peace plan.
However, late last night, Mr Radovan Karadzic, leader of the Bosnian Serbs,
disagreed with the former US president's interpretation of their talks which
were held in Pale, the Bosnian Serb capital. Mr Karadzic said there would
not be an immediate ceasefire but that he was willing to explore such a
possibility.
In advance of the talks Mr Carter stirred up controversy when he said that
Bosnian Serbs wanted peace and that Americans 'have primarily heard one side
of the story': that the Bosnian Serbs were the aggressors.
The White House, which has been sceptical of Mr Carter's latest peace foray
and has emphasised that it is not an official mission, immediately disputed
his assertion about which side was the aggressor. 'The Bosnian Serbs are the
aggressors in this war,' a White House spokeswoman said. 'I think the
American people have had an opportunity to see what's happening on the
ground there and to see both sides of the story.'
Mr Carter said after several hours of talks with Mr Karadzic, who had
invited him to undertake his mission, that he would return to Sarajevo to
put what he understood to be a ceasefire proposal to the Moslem-led Bosnian
government. Mr Carter said: 'The Bosnian Serb side agreed to an immediate
ceasefire and to negotiate a lasting cessation of hostilities.'
There was also controversy over whether the Bosnian Serbs had fulfilled
earlier pledges they gave Mr Carter. Since Mr Karadzic issued his promises
last week, Serb forces have attacked peacekeepers and civilian targets in
Sarajevo, blocked UN convoys and expelled more civilians from Serb-held
territory, UN officials said.
The Bosnian Serbs say publicly they have limited expectations from Mr
Carter's visit. But officials hint privately that the leadership in Pale may
be close to accepting a revised version of peace proposals first presented
by the five-member contact group in the summer. The original plan, they
believe, called on the Bosnian Serbs to withdraw from territory before talks
on complex issues such as agreed land swaps and links between the Bosnian
Serbs and what remains of Yugoslavia.
'The contact group plan has been changed,' an official said. The latest
version makes it clear that only a ceasefire and verbal commitment are
needed before negotiations begin. He said what the Serbs wanted was 'near to
independence. We are not looking for a seat at the UN. Our idea is to unite
with Serbia'. Unity would not preclude close economic and administrative
ties with the rest of Bosnia, he said. His remarks appeared at variance with
the frequent public insistence that only full, internationally recognised
sovereignty would satisfy Bosnia's Serbs.
</TEXT>
<XX>
