<HEADLINE>
FT  20 DEC 94 / BOC takes lead in giving more details on directors' pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The controversy surrounding top directors' pay has prompted BOC Group and
other leading companies to give shareholders more information about
executive packages.
BOC's annual report and accounts, sent to shareholders at the weekend, gives
full details for the first time of every director's remuneration package,
including pensions and share options.
The industrial gases company has so far moved furthest in providing pay
details. The group's chairman, Mr Richard Giordano, is also chairman of
British Gas, which has been at the heart of concerns over executive pay.
Next month, Grand Metropolitan, the food and drink conglomerate, is expected
to provide a similar level of detail in its accounts. 'We will go further
than ever before,' Grand Met said yesterday. Mr Giordano also sits on the
Grand Met board.
Earlier this year, Dixons, the electrical retail group, and Reuters, the
information services group, led the way by giving shareholders a far greater
amount of information on directors' pay than necessary under company law.
The government is examining the issue of executive pay after public anger at
recent large increases.
This follows the disclosure that Mr Cedric Brown, chief executive of British
Gas, had received a 75 per cent pay rise.
Mr Giordano has pledged British Gas will also give far more details on
directors' pay in its next annual report and accounts.
One leading BOC shareholder termed the new level of information the
'Giordano effect' and said: 'We can only welcome what he is getting
companies to do.'
The BOC report and accounts contains five pages of details on the directors'
pay packages, including details of each director's pension, in line with
information routinely given to shareholders in the US.
For example, the total benefit accrued to date for Dr Debajyoti Chatterji,
managing director of technology, has a lump sum value of Pounds 115,000.
Meanwhile, the Institute of Directors confirmed yesterday that it would be
issuing new guidelines on executive pay in the new year. It is likely to
stress that companies should make full disclosure of directors' pay details
and also recommend shorter service contracts.
</TEXT>
