FT  20 DEC 94 / Carter claims ceasefire deal in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Former US president Jimmy Carter claimed yesterday that the Bosnian Serbs
were willing to begin an immediate ceasefire and to discuss the
international peace plan for the former Yugoslavian republic.
Mr Carter, with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic during their talks at
the Serbian stronghold of Pale, said: 'The Bosnian Serb side agreed to an
immediate ceasefire and to negotiate a lasting cessation of hostilities.'
However, Mr Karadzic denied that his side had agreed to any ceasefire,
though he said he was willing to explore such a possibility. Mr Carter is
visiting Bosnia at Mr Karadzic's invitation in an effort to break the
deadlock in the peace negotiations.
The US administration has been sceptical of Mr Carter's latest peace foray
and has emphasised it is not an official mission.
